{"title_page": "Town & Country (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2001 film by Peter Chelsom}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Town & Country\n| image          = Town & Country.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Chelsom]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Simon Fields]]\n* [[Andrew Karsch]]\n* [[Fred Roos]]\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Buck Henry]]\n* [[Michael Laughlin]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Warren Beatty]]\n* [[Diane Keaton]]\n* [[Andie MacDowell]]\n* [[Garry Shandling]]\n* [[Jenna Elfman]]\n* [[Nastassja Kinski]]\n* [[Goldie Hawn]]}}\n| music          = [[Rolfe Kent]]\n| cinematography = [[William A. Fraker]]\n| editing        = [[Claire Simpson]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* FR Production\n* Longfellow Pictures\n* [[Sidney Kimmel#Sidney Kimmel Entertainment|Sidney Kimmel Entertainment]]\n* [[Simon Fields|Simon Fields Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[New Line Cinema]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2001|04|27}}\n| runtime        = 104 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 104:16--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/town-country-2001-4 | title=''TOWN & COUNTRY'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=May 15, 2001 | accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90 million<ref name=mojo/>\n| gross          = $10.4 million<ref name=mojo>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=townandcountry.htm |title=Town & Country (2001) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Town & Country''''' is a 2001 American [[romantic comedy|romantic comedy film]] directed by [[Peter Chelsom]], written by [[Buck Henry]] and [[Michael Laughlin]], and starring [[Warren Beatty]], [[Diane Keaton]], [[Goldie Hawn]], [[Garry Shandling]], [[Andie MacDowell]], [[Jenna Elfman]], [[Nastassja Kinski]], and [[Charlton Heston]].<ref name=\"Town & Country\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/331245/Town-Country/full-credits.html|title=Town & Country?|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|accessdate=May 22, 2016}}</ref> Beatty plays an architect, with Keaton as his wife, and Hawn and Shandling as their best friends. It was Beatty's and Keaton's first film together since 1981's ''[[Reds (film)|Reds]],'' and Beatty's third film with Hawn, after 1971's ''[[$ (film)|$]]'' and 1975's ''[[Shampoo (film)|Shampoo]]''.\n\nThe film is one of the [[List of biggest box office bombs|biggest box office flops]] in American film history, grossing a little over $10 million worldwide from a $90 million budget.<ref>[http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/records/budgets.php Movie Budget Records] from TheNumbers.com</ref> The film was Beatty's last appearance on screen for 15 years before he starred in ''[[Rules Don't Apply (film)|Rules Don't Apply]]'' in November 2016.\n\n==Plot==\nPorter Stoddard ([[Warren Beatty]]) is so prosperous an architect, he has New York homes on [[Park Avenue]] and in [[the Hamptons]], as well as a vacation lodge out west in [[Sun Valley, Idaho]]. He has been married for 25 years to the equally successful Ellie ([[Diane Keaton]]), an interior designer, but has been having an affair with Alex ([[Nastassja Kinski]]), a beautiful young cellist.\n\nThere is trouble brewing in the marriage of their best friends. Mona Morris ([[Goldie Hawn]]) wants a divorce from antique-dealer husband Griffin ([[Garry Shandling]]), after catching him having a hotel tryst. The part she did not catch is that Griffin's new romantic partner is a cross-dressing man. Mona wants to travel to Mississippi to see her girlhood antebellum home. Ellie is worried about Mona's depression over the state of her marriage and does not feel she should be alone, so Porter is asked to accompany Mona down south. There, they end up having a quick sexual fling.\n\nWith things awkward at home for both, Porter and Griffin fly by themselves to Sun Valley to get away from their troubles. But it is not long before Porter finds himself in a romantic entanglement with Eugenie Claybourne ([[Andie MacDowell]]), a spoiled heiress whose gun-loving father ([[Charlton Heston]]) is already loading his shotgun in case Porter does wrong by his daughter. A free spirit named Auburn ([[Jenna Elfman]]) also ends up coaxing Porter and Griffin to a Halloween party, where they end up dressed in preposterous costumes.\n\nBy the time Porter returns to New York, everything is falling apart, not only his home life but his house. And, once and for all, Griffin finds the nerve to tell his wife that he is leaving her for someone else, but it is not another woman.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Warren Beatty]] as Porter Stoddard\n* [[Diane Keaton]] as Ellie Stoddard\n* [[Goldie Hawn]] as Mona Morris\n* [[Garry Shandling]] as Griffin Morris\n* [[Andie MacDowell]] as Eugenie Claybourne\n* [[Jenna Elfman]] as Auburn\n* [[Nastassja Kinski]] as Alex\n* [[Charlton Heston]] as Mr. Claybourne\n* [[Marian Seldes]] as Mrs. Claybourne\n* [[Josh Hartnett]] as Tom Stoddard\n* Katharine Towne as Holly\n* [[Ian McNeice]] as Peter Principal\n* [[William Hootkins|Bill Hootkins]] as Barney\n* [[Terri Hoyos]] as Yolanda\n* [[Tricia Vessey]] as Alice\n* [[Azura Skye]] as Spider\n* [[Buck Henry]] as Suttler\n* [[Charlie Rose]] (archived footage) as himself\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe production costs of the film totaled an estimated US$90 million,<ref name=\"imdb_bus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0141907/business|title=Town & Country (2001) - Box office / business|accessdate=September 29, 2017|website=IMDb.com}}</ref> not including distribution and marketing expenses. The total worldwide box office came to $10,365,000.<ref name=\"imdb_bus\" /> Considering that typically half of the gross box office receipts go to the exhibitors and half to the filmmakers, ''Town & Country'' lost the studio at least $100 million, and probably much more if costs for distribution and marketing are considered, which average around $35\u201350 million for a studio picture such as this. The studio, having already spent in excess of $90 million, backed a limited distribution and marketing campaign in the $15\u201320 million range, bringing the total cost to $105\u2013110 million. However, some insiders have said that the total production costs were more likely in the $100\u2013105 million range, with the prints and ads at around $20 million, which would bring the total costs to $125 million.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===1998\u20131999===\nThe production itself began on June 8, 1998, on a budget of $44 million, including $10 million up front for Beatty. Filming was originally supposed to wrap by the fall of 1998 for a summer or fall 1999 release. Various problems occurred during filming, however, including Beatty's meticulous demand for many takes. Also, the script was still being developed, as writers were not satisfied with the ending originally written by [[Michael Laughlin]]. Various other screenwriters were brought in, including [[Paul Attanasio]] and [[Gary Ross]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Paul Attanasio Bio |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001921/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm |publisher=iMDB}}</ref> By April 1999, production was still going, but Shandling had to leave to do another film (''[[What Planet Are You From?]]''), as did Keaton (''[[Hanging Up]]'', which she also directed). It took a full year before they could gather the cast back together to film the new pages written by [[Buck Henry]]. Henry was hired for what was originally only going to be a few weeks of polish work. Eventually, he stayed on for several months and ended up earning (by some accounts) $3 million for rewriting roughly half of the script.  Henry has stated that he bought a new home with the money he made on this \"quick rewrite assignment.\"\n\n===2000 reshoots===\nReshoots were scheduled to begin on April 10, 2000, and were expected to last just a couple of weeks. However, filming continued through June 2000, when it finally wrapped two years after principal photography originally began. The reshoots included all of the new scenes, with screenwriter Buck Henry joining the cast as a divorce mediator. A new climax at a fashion gala involving all of the main female characters was written and filmed. Also, the closure scenes with Shandling and Hawn at the antique store and the scene with Beatty and Kinski on the street near the end were added. The scene between Beatty and Kinski in Manhattan as she is hailing a cab was actually filmed in downtown Los Angeles and was one of the last scenes filmed.\n\n==Reception==\nThe film finally made it into theaters on April 27, 2001, nearly three years after filming began, and received negative reviews from critics. On Rotten Tomatoes, the film has an approval rating of 13%, based on 91 reviews, with an average rating of 3.2/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Afflicted with extensive re-editing and re-writing, this sex comedy feels confusingly choppy. Also, the main characters are so wealthy and privileged that it's difficult to feel sympathy for their problems.\"<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/town_and_country/|title=Town & Country|website=Rottentomatoes.com|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> On Metacritic, the film has a score of 34 out of 100, based on 27 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".\n\nThe critic Nathan Rabin described it as \"the rare movie that can't seem to decide whether it wants to be ''[[Freddy Got Fingered]]'' or ''[[Hannah and Her Sisters]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/my-year-of-flops-case-file-84-town-country,10283/|title=My Year Of Flops Case File #84 Town & Country|first=Nathan|last=Rabin|website=Avclub.com|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> An article in ''The Hollywood Reporter'' lists ''Town & Country'' as the fifth-largest [[box office bomb]] of the 2000s.<ref>{{Citation | last = KIlday, Fernandez, & Kit | first = | title = Top 10 Movie Flops of the Decade | pages = | newspaper = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | location = [[Hollywood, California]] | date = 20 November 2009 | url =http://reporter.blogs.com/best_of_2000s/5-town-country-top-flops-of-the-decade.html | accessdate = <!-----28 November 2009----->}}</ref> In 2014, the ''Los Angeles Times'' listed the film as one of the most expensive box office flops of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-box-office-flops-pictures-photogallery.html|title=The costliest box office flops of all time|first=Los Angeles|last=Times|website=latimes.com|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Author James Robert Parish in his 2006 book, ''Fiasco&nbsp;\u2014 A History of Hollywood\u2019s Iconic Flops'', also states the film was a flop.<ref>{{cite book|last=Parish|first=James Robert|title=Fiasco&nbsp;\u2014 A History of Hollywood\u2019s Iconic Flops|location=[[Hoboken, New Jersey]]|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|year=2006|isbn=978-0471691594|url=https://archive.org/details/fiascohistoryofh00pari|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n** [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] \u2013 [[Peter Chelsom]] (nominated)\n** [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]] \u2013 [[Charlton Heston]] (also for ''[[Cats & Dogs]]'' and ''[[Planet of the Apes (2001 film)|Planet of the Apes]]'') ('''won''')\n** [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]] \u2013 [[Goldie Hawn]] (nominated)\n* [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]]\n** Worst Picture (nominated)\n** Worst Director \u2013 Peter Chelsom with unwanted assistance from [[Warren Beatty]] (nominated)\n** Most Painfully Unfunny Comedy (nominated)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0141907}}\n* {{Mojo title|townandcountry}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|town_and_country|}}\n* {{Metacritic film|town-country}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/15/arts/15LYMA.html?ex=1169960400&en=b6c9a41a52441280&ei=5070 \"Stumbling Toward a Theater Near You\"], a 2001 article from ''[[The New York Times]]'' on the making of ''Town & Country''.\n\n{{Peter Chelsom}}\n{{Buck Henry}}\n{{Michael Laughlin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Town And Country}}\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Chelsom]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael De Luca]]\n[[Category:Films set in Idaho]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Idaho]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Buck Henry]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Michael Laughlin]]\n[[Category:Midlife crisis films]]\n[[Category:New Line Cinema films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Rolfe Kent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2001 film by Peter Chelsom}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Town & Country\n| image          = Town & Country.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Chelsom]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Simon Fields]]\n* [[Andrew Karsch]]\n* [[Fred Roos]]\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Buck Henry]]\n* [[Michael Laughlin]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Warren Beatty]]\n* [[Diane Keaton]]\n* [[Andie MacDowell]]\n* [[Garry Shandling]]\n* [[Jenna Elfman]]\n* [[Nastassja Kinski]]\n* [[Goldie Hawn]]}}\n| music          = [[Rolfe Kent]]\n| cinematography = [[William A. Fraker]]\n| editing        = [[Claire Simpson]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* FR Production\n* Longfellow Pictures\n* [[Sidney Kimmel#Sidney Kimmel Entertainment|Sidney Kimmel Entertainment]]\n* [[Simon Fields|Simon Fields Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[New Line Cinema]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2001|04|27}}\n| runtime        = 104 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 104:16--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/town-country-2001-4 | title=''TOWN & COUNTRY'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=May 15, 2001 | accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90 million<ref name=mojo/>\n| gross          = $10.4 million<ref name=mojo>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=townandcountry.htm |title=Town & Country (2001) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Town & Country''''' is a 2001 American [[romantic comedy|romantic comedy film]] directed by [[Peter Chelsom]], written by [[Buck Henry]] and [[Michael Laughlin]], and starring [[Warren Beatty]], [[Diane Keaton]], [[Goldie Hawn]], [[Garry Shandling]], [[Andie MacDowell]], [[Jenna Elfman]], [[Nastassja Kinski]], and [[Charlton Heston]].<ref name=\"Town & Country\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/331245/Town-Country/full-credits.html|title=Town & Country?|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|accessdate=May 22, 2016}}</ref> Beatty plays an architect, with Keaton as his wife, and Hawn and Shandling as their best friends. It was Beatty's and Keaton's first film together since 1981's ''[[Reds (film)|Reds]],'' and Beatty's third film with Hawn, after 1971's ''[[$ (film)|$]]'' and 1975's ''[[Shampoo (film)|Shampoo]]''.\n\nThe film holds the distinction of being one of the [[List of biggest box office bombs|biggest box office flops]] in American film history, grossing a little over $10 million worldwide from a $90 million budget.<ref>[http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/records/budgets.php Movie Budget Records] from TheNumbers.com</ref> The film was Beatty's last appearance on screen for 15 years before he starred in ''[[Rules Don't Apply (film)|Rules Don't Apply]]'' in November 2016.\n\n==Plot==\nPorter Stoddard ([[Warren Beatty]]) is so prosperous an architect, he has New York homes on [[Park Avenue]] and in [[the Hamptons]], as well as a vacation lodge out west in [[Sun Valley, Idaho]]. He has been married for 25 years to the equally successful Ellie ([[Diane Keaton]]), an interior designer, but has been having an affair with Alex ([[Nastassja Kinski]]), a beautiful young cellist.\n\nThere is trouble brewing in the marriage of their best friends. Mona Morris ([[Goldie Hawn]]) wants a divorce from antique-dealer husband Griffin ([[Garry Shandling]]), after catching him having a hotel tryst. The part she did not catch is that Griffin's new romantic partner is a cross-dressing man. Mona wants to travel to Mississippi to see her girlhood antebellum home. Ellie is worried about Mona's depression over the state of her marriage and does not feel she should be alone, so Porter is asked to accompany Mona down south. There, they end up having a quick sexual fling.\n\nWith things awkward at home for both, Porter and Griffin fly by themselves to Sun Valley to get away from their troubles. But it is not long before Porter finds himself in a romantic entanglement with Eugenie Claybourne ([[Andie MacDowell]]), a spoiled heiress whose gun-loving father ([[Charlton Heston]]) is already loading his shotgun in case Porter does wrong by his daughter. A free spirit named Auburn ([[Jenna Elfman]]) also ends up coaxing Porter and Griffin to a Halloween party, where they end up dressed in preposterous costumes.\n\nBy the time Porter returns to New York, everything is falling apart, not only his home life but his house. And, once and for all, Griffin finds the nerve to tell his wife that he is leaving her for someone else, but it is not another woman.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Warren Beatty]] as Porter Stoddard\n* [[Diane Keaton]] as Ellie Stoddard\n* [[Goldie Hawn]] as Mona Morris\n* [[Garry Shandling]] as Griffin Morris\n* [[Andie MacDowell]] as Eugenie Claybourne\n* [[Jenna Elfman]] as Auburn\n* [[Nastassja Kinski]] as Alex\n* [[Charlton Heston]] as Mr. Claybourne\n* [[Marian Seldes]] as Mrs. Claybourne\n* [[Josh Hartnett]] as Tom Stoddard\n* Katharine Towne as Holly\n* [[Ian McNeice]] as Peter Principal\n* [[William Hootkins|Bill Hootkins]] as Barney\n* [[Terri Hoyos]] as Yolanda\n* [[Tricia Vessey]] as Alice\n* [[Azura Skye]] as Spider\n* [[Buck Henry]] as Suttler\n* [[Charlie Rose]] (archived footage) as himself\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===\n===\nThe production costs of the film totaled an estimated US$90 million,<ref name=\"imdb_bus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0141907/business|title=Town & Country (2001) - Box office / business|accessdate=September 29, 2017|website=IMDb.com}}</ref> not including distribution and marketing expenses. The total worldwide box office came to $10,365,000.<ref name=\"imdb_bus\" /> Considering that typically half of the gross box office receipts go to the exhibitors and half to the filmmakers, ''Town & Country'' lost the studio at least $100 million, and probably much more if costs for distribution and marketing are considered, which average around $35\u201350 million for a studio picture such as this. The studio, having already spent in excess of $90 million, backed a limited distribution and marketing campaign in the $15\u201320 million range, bringing the total cost to $105\u2013110 million. However, some insiders have said that the total production costs were more likely in the $100\u2013105 million range, with the prints and ads at around $20 million, which would bring the total costs to $125 million.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===1998\u20131999===\nThe production itself began on June 8, 1998, on a budget of $44 million, including $10 million up front for Beatty. Filming was originally supposed to wrap by the fall of 1998 for a summer or fall 1999 release. Various problems occurred during filming, however, including Beatty's meticulous demand for many takes. Also, the script was still being developed, as writers were not satisfied with the ending originally written by [[Michael Laughlin]]. Various other screenwriters were brought in, including [[Paul Attanasio]] and [[Gary Ross]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Paul Attanasio Bio |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001921/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm |publisher=iMDB}}</ref> By April 1999, production was still going, but Shandling had to leave to do another film (''[[What Planet Are You From?]]''), as did Keaton (''[[Hanging Up]]'', which she also directed). It took a full year before they could gather the cast back together to film the new pages written by [[Buck Henry]]. Henry was hired for what was originally only going to be a few weeks of polish work. Eventually, he stayed on for several months and ended up earning (by some accounts) $3 million for rewriting roughly half of the script.  Henry has stated that he bought a new home with the money he made on this \"quick rewrite assignment.\"\n\n===2000 reshoots===\nReshoots were scheduled to begin on April 10, 2000, and were expected to last just a couple of weeks. However, filming continued through June 2000, when it finally wrapped two years after principal photography originally began. The reshoots included all of the new scenes, with screenwriter Buck Henry joining the cast as a divorce mediator. A new climax at a fashion gala involving all of the main female characters was written and filmed. Also, the closure scenes with Shandling and Hawn at the antique store and the scene with Beatty and Kinski on the street near the end were added. The scene between Beatty and Kinski in Manhattan as she is hailing a cab was actually filmed in downtown Los Angeles and was one of the last scenes filmed.\n\n==Reception==\nThe film finally made it into theaters on April 27, 2001, nearly three years after filming began, and received negative reviews from critics. On Rotten Tomatoes, the film has an approval rating of 13%, based on 91 reviews, with an average rating of 3.2/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Afflicted with extensive re-editing and re-writing, this sex comedy feels confusingly choppy. Also, the main characters are so wealthy and privileged that it's difficult to feel sympathy for their problems.\"<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/town_and_country/|title=Town & Country|website=Rottentomatoes.com|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> On Metacritic, the film has a score of 34 out of 100, based on 27 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".\n\nThe critic Nathan Rabin described it as \"the rare movie that can't seem to decide whether it wants to be ''[[Freddy Got Fingered]]'' or ''[[Hannah and Her Sisters]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/my-year-of-flops-case-file-84-town-country,10283/|title=My Year Of Flops Case File #84 Town & Country|first=Nathan|last=Rabin|website=Avclub.com|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> An article in ''The Hollywood Reporter'' lists ''Town & Country'' as the fifth-largest [[box office bomb]] of the 2000s.<ref>{{Citation | last = KIlday, Fernandez, & Kit | first = | title = Top 10 Movie Flops of the Decade | pages = | newspaper = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | location = [[Hollywood, California]] | date = 20 November 2009 | url =http://reporter.blogs.com/best_of_2000s/5-town-country-top-flops-of-the-decade.html | accessdate = <!-----28 November 2009----->}}</ref> In 2014, the ''Los Angeles Times'' listed the film as one of the most expensive box office flops of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-box-office-flops-pictures-photogallery.html|title=The costliest box office flops of all time|first=Los Angeles|last=Times|website=latimes.com|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Author James Robert Parish in his 2006 book, ''Fiasco&nbsp;\u2014 A History of Hollywood\u2019s Iconic Flops'', also states the film was a flop.<ref>{{cite book|last=Parish|first=James Robert|title=Fiasco&nbsp;\u2014 A History of Hollywood\u2019s Iconic Flops|location=[[Hoboken, New Jersey]]|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|year=2006|isbn=978-0471691594|url=https://archive.org/details/fiascohistoryofh00pari|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n** [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] \u2013 [[Peter Chelsom]] (nominated)\n** [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]] \u2013 [[Charlton Heston]] (also for ''[[Cats & Dogs]]'' and ''[[Planet of the Apes (2001 film)|Planet of the Apes]]'') ('''won''')\n** [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]] \u2013 [[Goldie Hawn]] (nominated)\n\n* [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]]\n** Worst Picture (nominated)\n** Worst Director \u2013 Peter Chelsom with unwanted assistance from [[Warren Beatty]] (nominated)\n** Most Painfully Unfunny Comedy (nominated)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0141907}}\n* {{Mojo title|townandcountry}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|town_and_country|}}\n* {{Metacritic film|town-country}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/15/arts/15LYMA.html?ex=1169960400&en=b6c9a41a52441280&ei=5070 \"Stumbling Toward a Theater Near You\"], a 2001 article from ''[[The New York Times]]'' on the making of ''Town & Country''.\n\n{{Peter Chelsom}}\n{{Buck Henry}}\n{{Michael Laughlin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Town And Country}}\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Chelsom]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Michael De Luca]]\n[[Category:Films set in Idaho]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Film