sue_2/ismail.eng.asp New Balkan Politics \u2013 Journal of Politics]\n* [http://www.macedonians.co.uk/ Macedonians in the UK]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100305065457/http://www.umdiaspora.org/ United Macedonian Diaspora]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080629050307/http://www.smk.org.mk/ World Macedonian Congress]\n* [http://www.maticanaiselenici.com/ House of Immigrants]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in North Macedonia}}\n{{North Macedonia topics}}\n{{Slavic ethnic groups}}\n{{Eastern Christianity footer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macedonians (Ethnic Group)}}\n[[Category:Ethnic Macedonian people| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Albania]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Greece]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Macedonia (region)]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in North Macedonia]]\n[[Category:Slavic ethnic groups]]\n[[Category:South Slavs]]\n", "name_user": "StanProg", "label": "safe", "comment": "est.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macedonians_(ethnic_group)"}
{"title_page": "Blanche Monnier", "text_new": "{{Expand French|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = \n| image         = Blanche Monnier, 1901.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Blanche Monnier, shortly after being discovered in her locked room in 1901.\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1849|03|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Poitiers]], [[Second French Republic]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1913|10|13|1849|03|01|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Blois]], [[Third French Republic]]\n| nationality   = [[French people|French]]\n| other_names   = ''la S\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers''\n| occupation    = \n| years_active = \n| known_for     = Having been secretly incarcerated for a quarter-century\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Blanche Monnier''' ({{IPA-fr|bl\u0251\u0303\u0283 m\u0254nje}}; 1 March 1849 \u2013 13 October 1913), often known in France as '''''la S\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers'''''{{efn|Pronounced in French as a [[rhyme]] as {{IPA-fr|la sek\u025bst\u0281e d(\u0259) pwatje|}}.}} (roughly, \"The Confined Woman of Poitiers\"),<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Confined Woman of Poitiers|author1=Ivry, Benjamin|author2=Gide, Andr&#xe9;|year=2003|journal=New England Review (1990-)|volume=24|issue=3|pages=99\u2013132|jstor = 40244293}}</ref> was a woman from [[Poitiers]], [[France]], who was secretly kept locked in a small room by her aristocratic mother for 25 years. She was eventually found by police, then middle-aged and in an emaciated and filthy condition; according to officials, Monnier had not seen any [[sunlight]] for her entire captivity.<ref name=Vivi/>\n\n==Biography==\nMonnier was a French [[socialite]] from a well-respected, [[bourgeoisie]] family in [[Poitiers]] of old noble origins. She was renowned for her physical beauty, and attracted many potential suitors for marriage. In 1874, at the age of 25, she wanted to marry an older [[lawyer]] who was not to her mother Louise's liking; she argued that her daughter could not marry a \u201cpenniless lawyer\u201d.<ref name=\"eng\">See \"English sources\" under References section below.</ref> Her disapproving mother, angered by her daughter's defiance, locked her in a tiny, dark room in the [[attic]] of their home, where she kept her secluded for 25 years. Louise Monnier and her brother Marcel continued on with their daily lives, pretending to mourn Blanche's death. None of her friends knew where she was, and the lawyer she wished to marry unexpectedly died in 1885. On 23 May 1901, the \"Paris Attorney General\"{{efn|See ''[[Procureur g\u00e9n\u00e9ral]]''  for the closest translation of the office. At the time of writing, [[Paris]] was the capital of the [[French Third Republic]]; the \"Attorney General\" of Paris was [[L\u00e9on Bulot]] from 1900.}} received an anonymous letter {{endash}} the author of which is still unknown {{endash}} that revealed the [[incarceration]]:\n\n{{quote|{{wiktfr|Monsieur}} Attorney General: I have the honor to inform you of an exceptionally serious occurrence. I speak of a [[spinster]] who is locked up in ''Madame'' Monnier\u2019s house, half-starved and living on a putrid litter for the past twenty-five years \u2013 in a word, in her own filth.}} \n\nMonnier was rescued by police from appalling conditions, covered in old food and [[feces]], with bugs all around the bed and floor, weighing barely {{convert|25|kg|lb}}.<ref name=Pujolas/><ref name=CL/>\n\nOne policeman described the state of Monnier and her bed thus:<ref name=\"eng\" />\n\n{{quote|The unfortunate woman was lying completely naked on a rotten straw mattress. All around her was formed a sort of crust made from excrement, fragments of meat, vegetables, fish, and rotten bread\u2026 We also saw [[oyster]] shells, and bugs running across {{wiktfr|Mademoiselle}} Monnier\u2019s bed. The air was so unbreathable, the odor given off by the room was so rank, that it was impossible for us to stay any longer to proceed with our investigation.}}\n\nHer mother was arrested, became ill shortly afterwards, and died 15 days later after seeing an angry mob gather in front of her house. Her brother Marcel Monnier appeared in court, and was initially convicted, but later was [[acquitted]] on [[appeal]]; Marcel Monnier was deemed mentally incapacitated, and although the judges criticized his choices, they found that a \"[[duty to rescue]]\" did not exist in the penal code at that time with sufficient rule to convict him.<ref name=Pujolas/><ref name=Moreillon/>\n\nAfter she was released from the room, Monnier continued to suffer from mental health problems. She was diagnosed with various disorders, including [[anorexia nervosa]],{{efn|Then written in French as ''\"anorexie hyst\u00e9rique\"''.}} [[schizophrenia]], [[exhibitionism]], and [[coprophilia]]. This soon led to her admission to a [[psychiatric hospital]] in [[Blois]], France, where she eventually died in 1913 in apparent obscurity.<ref name=NR/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.retronews.fr/journal/le-petit-parisien/9-octobre-1901/2/86872/1/3a2a4d389a020761ea09f6116e0c8245?from=%2Fsearch%23allTerms%3D%2522blanche%2520monnier%2522%26sort%3Dscore%26page%3D1%26searchIn%3Dall%26total%3D845&index=1 |title=Retronews - Le site de presse de la BnF |language=fr |date=1999-12-31 |accessdate=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1930, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]] published a book about the incident, named ''La S\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers'', changing little but the names of the protagonists.<ref name=Pujolas/><ref name=Levy/> According to [[Herv\u00e9 Guibert]], this book was a great influence on the young [[Michel Foucault]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Genie (feral child)|Genie]]: A girl whose father kept her socially isolated until the age of 13 years and 7 months.\n* [[List of kidnappings]]\n* [[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: pre-1970]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<!--<ref name=Augustin>Augustin, Jean-Marie. ''L\u2019histoire v\u00e9ridique de la s\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers''. Fayard. 2001. {{ISBN|978-2213609515}}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=CL>{{cite web|url=http://www.charentelibre.fr/2014/05/19/jacques-pradel-et-rtl-revient-sur-l-incroyable-histoire-de-la-sequestree-de-poitiers,1896143.php|title=Jacques Pradel et RTL reviennent sur l'incroyable histoire de la S\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers|date=19 May 2015|publisher=Charente Libre|language=French}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Levy>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/villes/destins-de-femmes-21-04-2015-1923072_27.php|title=Destins de femmes: Ces Poitevines plus ou moins c\u00e9l\u00e8bres auront marqu\u00e9 l'Histoire|author=Levy, Audrey|date=21 April 2015|magazine=Le Point|language=French}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Moreillon>Moreillon, Laurent. L'infraction par omission, Librairie Droz, 1993, p. 65, (in French)</ref>\n\n<ref name=NR>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanouvellerepublique.fr/Loir-et-Cher/Loisirs/Livres-cd-dvd/n/Contenus/Articles/2015/04/25/Pascal-Audoux-devoile-les-mysteres-du-Loir-et-Cher-2308016|title=Pascal Audoux d\u00e9voile les myst\u00e8res du Loir-et-Cher|date=25 April 2015|publisher=La Nouvelle Republique|language=French}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Pujolas>{{cite web|url=http://culturebox.francetvinfo.fr/cinema/documentaire/un-documentaire-sur-lincroyable-affaire-de-la-sequestree-de-poitiers-212899|title=En tournage, un documentaire sur l'incroyable affaire de \"La s\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers\"|author=Pujolas, Marie|date=27 February 2015|publisher=France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions|language=French}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Vivi>Vivi, Janouin-Benanti. ''La S\u00e9questr\u00e9e De Poitiers: Une Affaire Judiciaire Sans Pr\u00e9c\u00e9dent'' (in French) {{ISBN|978-2914474009}}</ref>\n\n<!--<ref name=VN>''This Woman's Family Shockingly Locked Her Away In A Dungeon For 25 Years''. [http://www.viralnova.com/blanche-monnier/]</ref>-->\n\n}}\n;English sources\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.thevintagenews.com/2018/01/05/blanche-monnier/|title=Blanche Monnier was imprisoned in a tiny room for 25 years because her mother hated her choice of husband|author=Radeska, Tijana|date=5 January 2018|publisher=The Vintage News}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://historykey.com/story-nightmare-blanche-monnier/|title=The Story of a Nightmare: Blanche Monnier|publisher=History Key|access-date=30 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930154532/https://historykey.com/story-nightmare-blanche-monnier/|archive-date=30 September 2018|url-status=dead}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1901/06/09/archives/she-imprisoned-daughter-girl-kept-in-a-dungeon-twentyfive-years.html|title=She imprisoned daughter, Girl Kept in a Dungeon Twenty-five Years Because She Was True to Her Sweetheart|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=9 June 1901|accessdate=12 October 2017|url-access=subscription }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monnier, Blanche}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1900s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:1903 crimes]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century French people]]\n[[Category:19th-century French women]]\n[[Category:20th-century French people]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women]]\n[[Category:Formerly missing people]]\n[[Category:French people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:French victims of crime]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in France]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand French|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = \n| image         = Blanche Monnier, 1901.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Blanche Monnier, shortly after being discovered in her locked room in 1901.\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1849|03|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Poitiers]], [[Second French Republic]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1913|10|13|1849|03|01|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Blois]], [[Third French Republic]]\n| nationality   = [[French people|French]]\n| other_names   = ''la S\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers''\n| occupation    = \n| years_active = \n| known_for     = Having been secretly incarcerated for a quarter-century\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Blanche Monnier''' ({{IPA-fr|bl\u0251\u0303\u0283 m\u0254nje}}; 1 March 1849 \u2013 13 October 1913), often known in France as '''''la S\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers'''''{{efn|Pronounced in French as a [[rhyme]] as {{IPA-fr|la sek\u025bst\u0281e d(\u0259) pwatje|}}.}} (roughly, \"The Confined Woman of Poitiers\"),<ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Confined Woman of Poitiers|author1=Ivry, Benjamin|author2=Gide, Andr&#xe9;|year=2003|journal=New England Review (1990-)|volume=24|issue=3|pages=99\u2013132|jstor = 40244293}}</ref> was a woman from [[Poitiers]], [[France]], who was secretly kept locked in a small room by her aristocratic mother for 25 years. She was eventually found by police, then middle-aged and in an emaciated and filthy condition; according to officials, Monnier had not seen any [[sunlight]] for her entire captivity.<ref name=Vivi/>\n\n==Biography==\nMonnier was a French [[socialite]] from a well-respected, [[bourgeoisie]] family in [[Poitiers]] of old noble origins. She was renowned for her physical beauty, and attracted many potential suitors for marriage. In 1874, at the age of 25, she wanted to marry an older [[lawyer]] who was not to her mother Louise's liking; she argued that her daughter could not marry a \u201cpenniless lawyer\u201d.<ref name=\"eng\">See \"English sources\" under References section below.</ref> Her disapproving mother, angered by her daughter's defiance, locked her in a tiny, dark room in the [[attic]] of their home, where she kept her secluded for 25 years. Louise Monnier and her brother Marcel continued on with their daily lives, pretending to mourn Blanche's death. None of her friends knew where she was, and the lawyer she wished to marry unexpectedly died in 1885. On 23 May 1901, the \"Paris Attorney General\"{{efn|See ''[[Procureur g\u00e9n\u00e9ral]]''  for the closest translation of the office. At the time of writing, [[Paris]] was the capital of the [[Second French Empire]]; the \"Attorney General\" of Paris was [[L\u00e9on Bulot]] from 1900.}} received an anonymous letter {{endash}} the author of which is still unknown {{endash}} that revealed the [[incarceration]]:\n\n{{quote|{{wiktfr|Monsieur}} Attorney General: I have the honor to inform you of an exceptionally serious occurrence. I speak of a [[spinster]] who is locked up in ''Madame'' Monnier\u2019s house, half-starved and living on a putrid litter for the past twenty-five years \u2013 in a word, in her own filth.}} \n\nMonnier was rescued by police from appalling conditions, covered in old food and [[feces]], with bugs all around the bed and floor, weighing barely {{convert|25|kg|lb}}.<ref name=Pujolas/><ref name=CL/>\n\nOne policeman described the state of Monnier and her bed thus:<ref name=\"eng\" />\n\n{{quote|The unfortunate woman was lying completely naked on a rotten straw mattress. All around her was formed a sort of crust made from excrement, fragments of meat, vegetables, fish, and rotten bread\u2026 We also saw [[oyster]] shells, and bugs running across {{wiktfr|Mademoiselle}} Monnier\u2019s bed. The air was so unbreathable, the odor given off by the room was so rank, that it was impossible for us to stay any longer to proceed with our investigation.}}\n\nHer mother was arrested, became ill shortly afterwards, and died 15 days later after seeing an angry mob gather in front of her house. Her brother Marcel Monnier appeared in court, and was initially convicted, but later was [[acquitted]] on [[appeal]]; Marcel Monnier was deemed mentally incapacitated, and although the judges criticized his choices, they found that a \"[[duty to rescue]]\" did not exist in the penal code at that time with sufficient rule to convict him.<ref name=Pujolas/><ref name=Moreillon/>\n\nAfter she was released from the room, Monnier continued to suffer from mental health problems. She was diagnosed with various disorders, including [[anorexia nervosa]],{{efn|Then written in French as ''\"anorexie hyst\u00e9rique\"''.}} [[schizophrenia]], [[exhibitionism]], and [[coprophilia]]. This soon led to her admission to a [[psychiatric hospital]] in [[Blois]], France, where she eventually died in 1913 in apparent obscurity.<ref name=NR/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.retronews.fr/journal/le-petit-parisien/9-octobre-1901/2/86872/1/3a2a4d389a020761ea09f6116e0c8245?from=%2Fsearch%23allTerms%3D%2522blanche%2520monnier%2522%26sort%3Dscore%26page%3D1%26searchIn%3Dall%26total%3D845&index=1 |title=Retronews - Le site de presse de la BnF |language=fr |date=1999-12-31 |accessdate=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1930, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]] published a book about the incident, named ''La S\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers'', changing little but the names of the protagonists.<ref name=Pujolas/><ref name=Levy/> According to [[Herv\u00e9 Guibert]], this book was a great influence on the young [[Michel Foucault]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Genie (feral child)|Genie]]: A girl whose father kept her socially isolated until the age of 13 years and 7 months.\n* [[List of kidnappings]]\n* [[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: pre-1970]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<!--<ref name=Augustin>Augustin, Jean-Marie. ''L\u2019histoire v\u00e9ridique de la s\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers''. Fayard. 2001. {{ISBN|978-2213609515}}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=CL>{{cite web|url=http://www.charentelibre.fr/2014/05/19/jacques-pradel-et-rtl-revient-sur-l-incroyable-histoire-de-la-sequestree-de-poitiers,1896143.php|title=Jacques Pradel et RTL reviennent sur l'incroyable histoire de la S\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers|date=19 May 2015|publisher=Charente Libre|language=French}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Levy>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/villes/destins-de-femmes-21-04-2015-1923072_27.php|title=Destins de femmes: Ces Poitevines plus ou moins c\u00e9l\u00e8bres auront marqu\u00e9 l'Histoire|author=Levy, Audrey|date=21 April 2015|magazine=Le Point|language=French}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Moreillon>Moreillon, Laurent. L'infraction par omission, Librairie Droz, 1993, p. 65, (in French)</ref>\n\n<ref name=NR>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanouvellerepublique.fr/Loir-et-Cher/Loisirs/Livres-cd-dvd/n/Contenus/Articles/2015/04/25/Pascal-Audoux-devoile-les-mysteres-du-Loir-et-Cher-2308016|title=Pascal Audoux d\u00e9voile les myst\u00e8res du Loir-et-Cher|date=25 April 2015|publisher=La Nouvelle Republique|language=French}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Pujolas>{{cite web|url=http://culturebox.francetvinfo.fr/cinema/documentaire/un-documentaire-sur-lincroyable-affaire-de-la-sequestree-de-poitiers-212899|title=En tournage, un documentaire sur l'incroyable affaire de \"La s\u00e9questr\u00e9e de Poitiers\"|author=Pujolas, Marie|date=27 February 2015|publisher=France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions|language=French}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Vivi>Vivi, Janouin-Benanti. ''La S\u00e9questr\u00e9e De Poitiers: Une Affaire Judiciaire Sans Pr\u00e9c\u00e9dent'' (in French) {{ISBN|978-2914474009}}</ref>\n\n<!--<ref name=VN>''This Woman's Family Shockingly Locked Her Away In A Dungeon For 25 Years''. [http://www.viralnova.com/blanche-monnier/]</ref>-->\n\n}}\n;English sources\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.thevintagenews.com/2018/01/05/blanche-monnier/|title=Blanche Monnier was imprisoned in a tiny room for 25 years because her mother hated her choice of husband|author=Radeska, Tijana|date=5 January 2018|publisher=The Vintage News}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://historykey.com/story-nightmare-blanche-monnier/|title=The Story of a Nightmare: Blanche Monnier|publisher=History Key|access-date=30 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930154532/https://historykey.com/story-nightmare-blanche-monnier/|archive-date=30 September 2018|url-