{"title_page": "David Skegg", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=December 2017}}\n[[File:David Skegg.jpg|thumb|Professor David Skegg]]\n'''Sir David Christopher Graham Skegg''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|size=100%|KNZM|OBE|FRSNZ}} (born 16 December 1947) is a New Zealand epidemiologist and university administrator. He is a former [[Vice-Chancellor]] of the [[University of Otago]] and [[Professor]] of Preventive and Social Medicine. His primary research interest is cancer epidemiology.<ref name=kcoca>{{cite web |url=http://www.kcoca.com/courier.cfm?Page=CourierArticle&CourierArticleID=272 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040422021210/http://www.kcoca.com/courier.cfm?Page=CourierArticle&CourierArticleID=272 |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 April 2004 |accessdate=26 August 2010 |title=Old Collegian becomes Otago University Chancellor |year=2003 |publisher=[[King's College, Auckland|King's College]] }}</ref><ref name=critic>{{cite web|url=http://critic.co.nz/articles/335 |publisher=[[Critic (magazine)|Critic Magazine]] |year=2010 |last=Smirk |first=Susan |title=Skegg |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724192239/http://critic.co.nz/articles/335 |archivedate=24 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=otagomag>{{cite web|url=http://www.otago.ac.nz/news/otagomagazine/otago004395.pdf|title=To Lead|last=Rutherford|first=Jill|year=2004|work=Otago Magazine|publisher=University of Otago}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nSkegg was born in [[Auckland]] and attended [[King's College, Auckland]]. He entered the medical course at the [[University of Otago]], travelling on exchange to [[Harvard University]]. He later received a (postgraduate) [[Rhodes Scholarship]] to the [[University of Oxford]], joining [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol College]] and working with noted epidemiologist [[Richard Doll|Sir Richard Doll]].<ref name=kcoca/><ref name=acu>{{cite web |url=http://www.adelaide.edu.au/acu2006/program/speakers.html |publisher=Association of Commonwealth Universities |title=Conference of Executive Heads: Invited Speakers |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312023621/http://www.adelaide.edu.au/acu2006/program/speakers.html |archivedate=12 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nReturning to Otago, Skegg took up the departmental chair in Preventive and Social Medicine in 1980. In 2004, he took up the Vice-Chancellorship of the university. He stood down from that position in 2011. He was appointed President of the [[Royal Society of New Zealand]] in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalsociety.org.nz/2012/03/12/new-president/|title=Royal Society of New Zealand announces new President|publisher=Royal Society of New Zealand|date=12 March 2012|access-date=16 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208162022/http://www.royalsociety.org.nz/2012/03/12/new-president/|archive-date=8 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSkegg has acted as a consultant to the [[World Health Organization]] and to the [[Government of New Zealand|New Zealand government]]. He chaired the Health Research Council, the Science Board, and the Public Health Commission.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1089437275|title=The health of the people|last=Skegg|first=David|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|year=2019|isbn=9781988545585|location=Wellington, New Zealand|pages=141|oclc=1089437275}}</ref> In 1990, he was appointed an OBE for services to medicine and, in the [[2009 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|2009 New Year Honours]], he was appointed a [[New Zealand Order of Merit|Distinguished Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]], also for services to medicine.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/new-year-honours-list-2009 | title=New Year honours list 2009|date=31 December 2008 | publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet | accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> Later in 2009, he accepted re-designation as a Knight Companion following the restoration of titular honours by the New Zealand government.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/special-honours-list-1-august-2009 | title=Special honours list 1 August 2009|date=1 August 2008 | publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet | accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> He has contributed to the study of cervical, breast and prostate cancer, as well contraceptives and reproductive health.<ref name=nzh>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10550120|date=31 December 2008|title=Honours List: Cancer researcher lifted lid on healthcare faults|last=Johnston|first=Martin|work=The New Zealand Herald}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* Hancock, Farah (2019). [https://www.newsroom.co.nz/2019/04/16/531451/nzs-deadly-public-health-battle \"NZ's deadly public health battle\".] ''Newsroom'', 16 April 2019.\n* [https://www.radionz.co.nz/national/programmes/ninetonoon/audio/2018685317/sir-david-skegg-national-leadership-on-public-health-needed \"Sir David Skegg: national leadership on public health needed.\"] ''RNZ,'' 6 March 2019.\n* {{cite book |author= Lambert, Max |title= Who's Who in New Zealand |year=1991|edition= 12th |publisher= Reed, Auckland |page= 583 |quote= | url= |isbn= 0 7900 01306 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skegg, David}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Otago faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Otago alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:New Zealand public health doctors]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Vice-Chancellors of the University of Otago]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Royal Society of New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=December 2017}}\n[[File:David Skegg.jpg|thumb|Professor David Skegg]]\n'''Sir David Christopher Graham Skegg''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|size=100%|KNZM|OBE|FRSNZ}} (born 16 December 1947) is a New Zealand epidemiologist and university administrator. He is a former [[Vice-Chancellor]] of the [[University of Otago]] and [[Professor]] of Preventive and Social Medicine. His primary research interest is cancer epidemiology.<ref name=kcoca>{{cite web |url=http://www.kcoca.com/courier.cfm?Page=CourierArticle&CourierArticleID=272 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040422021210/http://www.kcoca.com/courier.cfm?Page=CourierArticle&CourierArticleID=272 |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 April 2004 |accessdate=26 August 2010 |title=Old Collegian becomes Otago University Chancellor |year=2003 |publisher=[[King's College, Auckland|King's College]] }}</ref><ref name=critic>{{cite web|url=http://critic.co.nz/articles/335 |publisher=[[Critic (magazine)|Critic Magazine]] |year=2010 |last=Smirk |first=Susan |title=Skegg |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724192239/http://critic.co.nz/articles/335 |archivedate=24 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=otagomag>{{cite web|url=http://www.otago.ac.nz/news/otagomagazine/otago004395.pdf|title=To Lead|last=Rutherford|first=Jill|year=2004|work=Otago Magazine|publisher=University of Otago}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nSkegg was born in [[Auckland]] and attended [[King's College, Auckland]]. He entered the medical course at the [[University of Otago]], travelling on exchange to [[Harvard University]]. He later received a (postgraduate) [[Rhodes Scholarship]] to the [[University of Oxford]], joining [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol College]] and working with noted epidemiologist [[Richard Doll|Sir Richard Doll]].<ref name=kcoca/><ref name=acu>{{cite web |url=http://www.adelaide.edu.au/acu2006/program/speakers.html |publisher=Association of Commonwealth Universities |title=Conference of Executive Heads: Invited Speakers |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312023621/http://www.adelaide.edu.au/acu2006/program/speakers.html |archivedate=12 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nReturning to Otago, Skegg took up the departmental chair in Preventive and Social Medicine in 1980. In 2004, he took up the Vice-Chancellorship of the university. He stood down from that position in 2011. He was appointed President of the [[Royal Society of New Zealand]] in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalsociety.org.nz/2012/03/12/new-president/|title=Royal Society of New Zealand announces new President|publisher=Royal Society of New Zealand|date=12 March 2012|access-date=16 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208162022/http://www.royalsociety.org.nz/2012/03/12/new-president/|archive-date=8 February 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSkegg has acted as a consultant to the [[World Health Organization]] and to the [[Government of New Zealand|New Zealand government]]. He chaired the Health Research Council, the Science Board, and the Public Health Commission.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1089437275|title=The health of the people|last=Skegg|first=David|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|year=2019|isbn=9781988545585|location=Wellington, New Zealand|pages=141|oclc=1089437275}}</ref> In 1990, he was appointed an OBE for services to medicine and, in the [[2009 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|2009 New Year Honours]], he was appointed a [[New Zealand Order of Merit|Distinguished Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]], also for services to medicine.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/new-year-honours-list-2009 | title=New Year honours list 2009|date=31 December 2008 | publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet | accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> Later in 2009, he accepted re-designation as a Knight Companion following the restoration of titular honours by the New Zealand government.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/special-honours-list-1-august-2009 | title=Special honours list 1 August 2009|date=1 August 2008 | publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet | accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> He has contributed to the study of cervical, breast and prostate cancer, as well contraceptives and reproductive health.<ref name=nzh>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10550120|date=31 December 2008|title=Honours List: Cancer researcher lifted lid on healthcare faults|last=Johnston|first=Martin|work=The New Zealand Herald}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n\n* Hancock, Farah (2019). [https://www.newsroom.co.nz/2019/04/16/531451/nzs-deadly-public-health-battle \"NZ's deadly public health battle\".] ''Newsroom'', 16 April 2019.\n* [https://www.radionz.co.nz/national/programmes/ninetonoon/audio/2018685317/sir-david-skegg-national-leadership-on-public-health-needed \"Sir David Skegg: national leadership on public health needed.\"] ''RNZ,'' 6 March 2019.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book |author= Lambert, Max |title= Who's Who in New Zealand |year=1991|edition= 12th |publisher= Reed, Auckland |page= 583 |quote= | url= |isbn= 0 7900 01306 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skegg, David}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Otago faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Otago alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:New Zealand public health doctors]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Vice-Chancellors of the University of Otago]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Royal Society of New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "Order", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Skegg"}
{"title_page": "Boston Navy Yard", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{confused|text=[[Charleston Naval Shipyard]] in North Charleston, South Carolina}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2008}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name =Boston Naval Shipyard\n| nrhp_type = nhld\n| nocat = yes\n| image = Charlestown_Navy_Yard_Mystic_Wharf_Map_1912.jpg\n| caption = 1912 Map of the Charlestown Navy Yard and Mystic Wharf\n| location= Southeast of Chelsea Street, Charlestown, [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| area =\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|22|34|N|71|3|9|W|display=inline,title}}\n| built =1800\n| architect= Alexander Parris, et al.\n| architecture= \n| added = 15 November 1966\n| governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n| refnum=66000134<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Infobox Military Structure \t\n|name= Boston Navy Shipyard\n|location= [[Boston]], Massachusetts\t\n|image= \n|caption= \n|type= Shipyard\t\n|built= 1800\n|materials=\t\n|used= 1801\u20131975\n|controlledby=\t[[United States Navy]]\n|garrison= \n|commanders= \n|battles=\t\n}}\n\nThe '''Boston Navy Yard''', originally called the '''Charlestown Navy Yard''' and later '''Boston Naval Shipyard''', was one of the oldest [[shipbuilding]] facilities in the [[United States Navy]]. It was established in 1801 as part of the recent establishment of the new [[United States Department of the Navy|U.S. Department of the Navy]] in 1798. After 175 years of military service, it was decommissioned as a naval installation on 1 July 1974.\n\nThe {{convert|30|acre|ha|sing=on}} property is administered by the [[National Park Service]], becoming part of [[Boston National Historical Park]]. Enough of the yard remains in operation to support the moored [[USS Constitution|USS ''Constitution'']] (\"Old Ironsides\") of 1797, built as one of the [[Original six frigates of the United States Navy|original six heavy frigates]] for the revived American navy, and the oldest warship still commissioned in the [[United States Navy]].   {{USS|Cassin Young|DD-793}}, a 1943 [[World War II]]-era [[Fletcher-class destroyer|''Fletcher''-class]] [[destroyer]] serving as a [[museum ship]], is also berthed here. The museum area includes a dock which is a stop on the [[MBTA Boat]] water transport system.  Among local people in the area and the National Park Service, it is still known as the Charlestown Navy Yard.<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/bost/bost_lographics/cnyintro.htm Charlestown Navy Yard, National Park Service] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041207161516/http://www.nps.gov/bost/bost_lographics/cnyintro.htm |date=7 December 2004 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[South Boston Naval Annex]] was located along the [[South Boston Waterfront|waterfront]] in [[South Boston]].\n\n==History==\nThe earliest naval shipbuilding activities in [[Charlestown, Massachusetts]] across the [[Charles River]] and [[Boston harbor]] to the north from the city of [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], began during the [[American Revolutionary War]] (1775\u20131783). The Charlestown Arsenal of [[United States Army]] was established in 1794.<ref name=Thomas>{{cite book|last1=Thomas|first1=Matthew|title=Historic Powder Houses of New England: Arsenals of American Independence|date=2013|publisher=[[The History Press]]|page=80}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, in 1800, the land for the Charlestown Navy Yard was purchased by the United States government and the yard itself was established. The yard built the first U.S. [[ship of the line]], {{USS|Independence|1814|6}}, but was primarily a repair and storage facility until the 1890s, when it started to build steel ships for the \"New Navy\". By then, it was called the Boston Navy Yard.\n\nOn 24 June 1833, the staff and dignitaries including then Vice President [[Martin Van Buren]], [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Lewis Cass]], [[Secretary of the Navy]] [[Levi Woodbury]], and many Massachusetts officials, witnessed \"one of the great events of American naval history\": the early United States [[frigate]] {{USS|Constitution||2}} was inaugurating the first naval [[drydock]] in [[New England]] designed by prominent civil engineer [[Loammi Baldwin, Jr.]]<ref name=\"hnsa\">[http://www.hnsa.org/conf2004/papers/carlson.htm Historic Naval Ships Association] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301102119/http://www.hnsa.org/conf2004/papers/carlson.htm |date=1 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Charlestown Ropewalk|ropewalk]] supplied cordage used in the Navy from the time it opened in 1837 until the Yard closed in 1975. After the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] (1861\u20131865), the Yard was downgraded to an Equipment and Recruit Facility.<ref name=\"cnyhist\" />\n\nIn the late 1880s and 1890s, the Navy began expanding again bringing into service new modern steel hulled steam-powered warships and that brought new life to the Yard.  In the first years of the 20th century, a second drydock was added. During [[World War II]] (1939/1941\u20131945), it worked to fix [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Royal Navy]] warships and merchant transports damaged by the [[Nazi Germany|Nazi Germans]] when crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|North Atlantic Ocean]].  On 27 September 1941\u2014[[Liberty Fleet Day (Victory Fleet Day)|Liberty Fleet Day]]\u2014Boston launched two [[destroyer]]s, USS ''Cowie'' and the USS ''Knight''.  Even before the U.S. entered the Second World War after the [[Pearl Harbor]] attack on 7 December 1941, a month before in November, Boston was one of four United States naval shipyards selected to build {{sclass2-|Captain|frigate|1}}s under the [[Lend-Lease]] military assistance program for the Royal Navy. Since the United States was at war when these ships were finally completed, some were later requisitioned and used by the United States Navy as [[destroyer escort]]s.<ref>Franklin, Bruce Hampton (1999) ''The Buckley-class Destroyer Escorts'' Naval Institute Press {{ISBN|1-55750-280-3}} p.7</ref> In the post war period, the shipyard modified World War II ships for [[Cold War]] (1945\u20131991) service through [[Fleet Rehabilitation and Modernization]] (FRAM). The [[Korean War]] (1950\u20131953), and [[Vietnam War]] (1964\u20131975) did not bring much work to the yard since it was so far from the fighting.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}<!-- confirm reason -->\n\n==Ships built at Boston Navy Yard==\n[[File:Aerial view of the Boston Naval Shipyard in April 1960.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of the Boston Navy Yard in April 1960.]]\n[[File:Boston Naval Shipyard 1958.jpg|thumb|The [[South Boston Naval Annex]], circa 1958]]\n* 1814: {{USS|Independence|1814|6}} (90-gun [[ship of the line]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/i1/independence-ii.htm |title=Independence |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203023415/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/i1/independence-ii.htm |archivedate=3 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[War of 1812]]; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]\n* 1825: {{USS|Boston|1825|6}} (18-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/b8/boston-iv.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060724050236/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/b8/boston-iv.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 July 2006 |title=Boston |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 }}</ref> [[Mexican\u2013American War]]\n* 1827: {{USS|Warren|1827|6}} (20-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/w3/warren-iv.htm |title=Warren |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110412041840/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/w3/warren-iv.htm |archivedate=12 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Mexican\u2013American War]]\n* 1827: {{USS|Falmouth|1827|6}} (24-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/f1/falmouth.htm |title=Falmouth |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030235819/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/f1/falmouth.htm |archivedate=30 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Mexican\u2013American War]]\n* 1837: {{USS|Cyane|1837|6}} (22-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c16/cyane-ii.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040313233041/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c16/cyane-ii.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2004 |title=Cyane |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 }}</ref> [[Mexican\u2013American War]]; [[American Civil War]]\n* 1839: {{USS|Marion|1839|6}} (16-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/m5/marion.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040314002559/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/m5/marion.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 March 2004 |title=Marion |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 }}</ref> [[American Civil War]]\n* 1842: {{USS|Cumberland|1842|6}} (50-gun [[sailing frigate|frigate]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c16/cumberland-i.htm |title=Cumberland |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204014811/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c16/cumberland-i.htm |archivedate=4 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Mexican\u2013American War]]; [[Battle of Hampton Roads]]\n* 1844: {{USS|Plymouth|1844|6}} (22-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/p8/plymouth-i.htm |title=Plymouth |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212230451/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/p8/plymouth-i.htm |archivedate=12 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Perry Expedition]]\n* 1848: {{USS|Vermont|1848|6}} (74-gun [[ship of the line]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/v2/vermont-i.htm |title=Vermont |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213015213/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/v2/vermont-i.htm |archivedate=13 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[American Civil War]]\n* 1858: {{USS|Hartford|1858|6}} (22-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/h3/hartford.htm |title=Hartford |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212230746/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/h3/hartford.htm |archivedate=12 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Battle of Forts Jackson and St. Philip]]; [[Battle of Mobile Bay]]\n* 1859: {{USS|Narragansett|1859|6}} (5-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/n1/narragansett-i.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040317224638/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/n1/narragansett-i.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 March 2004 |title=Narragansett |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 }}</ref> [[American Civil War]]\n* 1861: {{USS|Wachusett|1861|6}} (10-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/w1/wachusett-i.htm |title=Wachusett |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213015216/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/w1/wachusett-i.htm |archivedate=13 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Peninsula Campaign]]; [[Bahia incident]]\n* 1861: {{USS|Housatonic|1861|6}} (11-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/h8/housatonic-i.htm |title=Housatonic |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213014735/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/h8/housatonic-i.htm |archivedate=13 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Sinking of USS Housatonic]]\n* 1861: {{USS|Maratanza|1861|6}} (side-wheel steam gunboat)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/m3/maratanza-i.htm |title=Maratanza |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=13 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214021326/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/m3/maratanza-i.htm |archivedate=14 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Peninsula Campaign]]; [[First Battle of Fort Fisher]]; [[Second Battle of Fort Fisher]]\n* 1862: {{USS|Canandaigua|1862|6}} (6-gun [[sloop of war]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c2/canandaigua-i.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040315063830/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c2/canandaigua-i.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 March 2004 |title=Canandaigua |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[United States Navy]] |accessdate=12 December 2013 }}</ref> [[American Civil War]]\n* 1862: {{USS|Tioga|1862|6}} (side-wheel steam gunboat)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/t6/tioga-i.htm |title=Tioga |website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]] |publisher=[[Uni