attle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: HMS {{HMS|Loring|K565|2}} ([[Captain-class frigate]])<ref name=\"lenton\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: HMS {{HMS|Hoste|K566|2}} ([[Captain-class frigate]])<ref name=\"lenton\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: HMS {{HMS|Moorsom|K567|2}} ([[Captain-class frigate]])<ref name=\"lenton\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: HMS {{HMS|Manners|K568|2}} ([[Captain-class frigate]])<ref name=\"lenton\"/> shared credit for sinking [[German submarine U-1051|''U-1051'']]\n* 1943: HMS {{HMS|Mounsey|K569|2}} ([[Captain-class frigate]])<ref name=\"lenton\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: HMS {{HMS|Inglis|K570|2}} ([[Captain-class frigate]])<ref name=\"lenton\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: HMS {{HMS|Inman|K571|2}} ([[Captain-class frigate]])<ref name=\"lenton\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: {{USS|O'Toole|DE-527}} ([[Evarts-class destroyer escort|''Evarts''-class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone157\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: {{USS|John J. Powers|DE-528}} ([[Evarts-class destroyer escort|''Evarts''-class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone157\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: {{USS|Mason|DE-529}} ([[Evarts-class destroyer escort|''Evarts''-class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone157\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: {{USS|John M. Bermingham|DE-530}} ([[Evarts-class destroyer escort|''Evarts''-class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone157\"/> [[Battle of the Atlantic]]\n* 1943: {{USS|Edward H. Allen|DE-531}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\">Silverstone, Paul H. ''U.S. Warships of World War II'' (1968) Doubleday & Company p.175</ref> rescued crew of the [[SS Andrea Doria|SS ''Andrea Doria'']]\n* 1943: {{USS|Tweedy|DE-532}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/>\n* 1943: {{USS|Howard F. Clark|DE-533}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''-class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/> [[Battle for Leyte Gulf]]; [[Battle of Okinawa]]\n* 1943: {{USS|Silverstein|DE-534}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/> [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater of Operations]]; [[Korean War]]\n* 1943: {{USS|Lewis|DE-535}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/> [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater of Operations]]\n* 1943: {{USS|Bivin|DE-536}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/> [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater of Operations]]\n* 1943: {{USS|Rizzi|DE-537}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/>\n* 1943: {{USS|Osberg|DE-538}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/>\n* 1944: {{USS|Amberjack|SS-522}} ([[Tench-class submarine|''Tench''-class submarine]])<ref name=Bauer281>{{cite book | last = Bauer | first = K. Jack | authorlink = K. Jack Bauer | author2=Roberts, Stephen S. | title = Register of Ships of the U.S. Navy, 1775-1990: Major Combatants | publisher = Greenwood Press | year = 1991 | location = [[Westport, Connecticut]] | page = 281 | url = | doi = | isbn = 0-313-26202-0 }}</ref>\n* 1944: {{USS|Grampus|SS-523}} ([[Tench-class submarine|''Tench''-class submarine]])<ref name=Bauer281/>\n* 1944: {{USS|Pickerel|SS-524}} ([[Tench-class submarine|''Tench''-class submarine]])<ref name=Bauer281/>\n* 1944: {{USS|Grenadier|SS-525}} ([[Tench-class submarine|''Tench''-class submarine]])<ref name=Bauer281/>\n* 1945: {{USS|Donner|LSD-20}} ([[Casa Grande-class dock landing ship|''Casa Grande''-class dock landing ship]])<ref name=\"silverstone263\">Silverstone, Paul H. ''U.S. Warships of World War II'' (1968) Doubleday & Company pp.263&266</ref> [[Mercury-Redstone 2]] recovery\n* 1945: {{USS|Fort Mandan|LSD-21}} ([[Casa Grande-class dock landing ship|''Casa Grande''-class dock landing ship]])<ref name=\"silverstone263\"/>\n* 1945: {{USS|Tortuga|LSD-26}} ([[Casa Grande-class dock landing ship|''Casa Grande''-class dock landing ship]])<ref name=\"silverstone263\"/> [[Korean War]]; [[Vietnam War]]\n* 1945: {{USS|Whetstone|LSD-27}} ([[Casa Grande-class dock landing ship|''Casa Grande''-class dock landing ship]])<ref name=\"silverstone263\"/> [[Korean War]]; [[Vietnam War]]\n* 1955: {{USS|Wagner|DER-539}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/>\n* 1955: {{USS|Vandivier|DER-540}} ([[John C. Butler-class destroyer escort|''John C. Butler''\u2013class destroyer escort]])<ref name=\"silverstone175\"/>\n\n== Current use ==\nThe Yard closed after the Vietnam War. When ideas were floated for redevelopment of the yard, one popular idea was to have the yard turned into a construction yard for [[oil tanker]]s.<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,942895,00.html|title=NEW ENGLAND: Bases for Sale|date=1 July 1974|publisher=Time, Inc.|accessdate=4 November 2009|location=New England}}</ref> Ultimately, these plans fell through, and the site became part of the [[Boston National Historical Park]]. Its mission is, \"to interpret the art and history of naval shipbuilding\".<ref name=\"cnyhist\">[http://www.nps.gov/archive/bost/bost_lographics/cnyhist.htm Charlestown Navy Yard: The Shipyard on the Charles] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070101021552/http://www.nps.gov/archive/bost/bost_lographics/cnyhist.htm |date=1 January 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe Boston Navy Yard hosts many attractions, including [[Charlestown Naval Shipyard Park]]. The fully commissioned {{USS|Constitution}} and the [[museum ship]] {{USS|Cassin Young|DD-793}} are tied up at Pier 1 and open to the public.<ref>As ''Constitution'' is a US Navy ship, consult [http://www.ussconstitution.navy.mil/ her official website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070213180914/http://www.ussconstitution.navy.mil/ |date=13 February 2007 }} before visiting.</ref> The Navy Yard also hosts the [[USS Constitution Museum|USS ''Constitution'' Museum]]. Dry Dock No. 1 is still used for ship maintenance for ''Constitution'' and ''Cassin Young''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.hnsa.org/conf2004/papers/carlson.htm |title=Dry Dock No. 1, Charlestown Navy Yard |last=Carlson |first=Stephen P. |work=Historic Naval Ships Association |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref> In May 2015, ''Constitution'' entered the dry dock for three years of repairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.usni.org/2015/05/19/uss-constitution-enters-dry-dock-for-three-years-of-repairs |title=USS Constitution Enters Dry Dock for Three Years of Repairs |last=LaGrone |first=Sam |work=USNI News |date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Yard is toward the north end of the [[Freedom Trail]]. The [[MBTA Boat]] stops at nearby Pier 4, providing easy visitor access to the Yard. The campus of the [[MGH Institute of Health Professions]] occupies seven buildings in the Yard, including classroom, office, and clinical space.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\" class=center>\nImage:USS Cassin Young 2007.jpg|USS ''Cassin Young'' berthed at the Boston Navy Yard\nFile:Dry Dock 1.JPG|A view of the dry dock without water\nFile:Boston Dry Dock.JPG|''Cassin Young'' in drydock\nFile:USS Cassin Young in Dry Dock.JPG|''Cassin Young'' in dry dock at night\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Port of Boston]]\n* [[List of National Historic Landmarks in Boston]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in northern Boston, Massachusetts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Co